  {
    "user": "UFEQUBNNT",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1731876985.684289",
    "client_msg_id": "1D9A99F5-7030-47FA-8F9D-04472396B3DE",
    "text": "It’s that layout algorithm where you ask all of your subviews, “How big would you want to be if you had [this much space]?” then tell them, “Okay, I’m giving you [this much space], lay out your subviews.”\n\nI don’t know the name for it! But it meant the table was easy: it just takes max() of all the heights and widths for the cells in every row and column.\n\nI draw the wires in a second pass using the world coordinates of the THREE.Object3Ds post-layout.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1731834056.506809",
    "parent_user_id": "UFEQUBNNT",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "Pwi/0",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "It’s that layout algorithm where you ask all of your subviews, “How big would you want to be if you had [this much space]?” then tell them, “Okay, I’m giving you [this much space], lay out your subviews.”\n\nI don’t know the name for it! But it meant the table was easy: it just takes max() of all the heights and widths for the cells in every row and column.\n\nI draw the wires in a second pass using the world coordinates of the THREE.Object3Ds post-layout"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
